nt approach. Maybe write a lemma that `(support p).length ≤ (darts p).length + 1` because each new edge can add at most one new vertex. Then since `(supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length`, `(edgeSet p).card ≤ (darts p).length` (since `card` is less than length, or equal if no duplicates), we would get `(supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length ≤ (darts p).length + 1 ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 + 1`, which doesn't directly help.\n\n   Hmm. Actually, perhaps better to look directly at the following:\n   - For any walk, `(support p) = [v₁, v₂, ..., v_{k+1}]`, and `darts p = [(v₁, v₂), (v₂, v₃), ..., (v_k, v_{k+1})]`. So the support has length `k+1`, darts has length `k`.\n   - Hence, `supportSet p ⊆ support p`, so `(supportSet p).card ≤ k+1`.\n   - But `edgeSet p` is the set of edges in darts p, which is at least `k` edges if all are distinct.\n   - Hence, if we could prove that `k+1 ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1`, i.e., `k ≤ (edgeSet p).card`, then the inequality follows.\n   - Indeed `(edgeSet p).card = k - number of duplicate edges`, but since `darts p` has length `k`, then `(edgeSet p).card ≤ k`, so `k ≤ (edgeSet p).card` is false in general.\n   - For example, if all edges are the same, then `(edgeSet p).card = 1`, but `(supportSet p).card = 2`. But in that case the inequality becomes `2 ≤ 1 + 1 = 2`, which is correct.\n\n   So perhaps my first thought that `(supportSet p).card ≤ k + 1` is fine, and `(edgeSet p).card ≤ k`, but the inequality is `≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1`.\n\n   Let me think about the worst case, suppose all edges are the same. Then:\n   - `supportSet p = {v₁, v₂}` (assuming the walk is `v₁ → v₂ → v₁ → v₂ ...`; say length 2n + 1, then supportSet.card = 2, and edgeSet.card = 1, 2 ≤ 1 + 1 holds).\n   - Alternatively if it is `v → v`, then it's `supportSet.card = 1`, edgeSet.card = 1, 1 ≤ 1 +1 holds.\n   So even in the worst case it holds.\n\n   So perhaps inductively, the inequality is always true. Maybe try:\n\n#### Revised Inductive Proof:\n1. Base case: `p = nil`.\n   - `supportSet p = {u}` → cardinality 1.\n   - `edgeSet p = ∅` → cardinality 0.\n   - 1 ≤ 0 + 1 is true.\n\n2. Case: `p = cons h p'`, i.e., we add an edge from `u` to `v'` (but in general, this is not easy because it depends on whether `u` is already in the support of `p'` or not).\n\n   But actually, perhaps a better approach is to note that `supportSet p ⊆ support p` and `support p` is the list `[u] ++ p'.support` (for `cons`), so `supportSet p ⊆ insert u (supportSet p')`, which implies `card (supportSet p) ≤ card (supportSet p') + 1`.\n\n   On the other hand, `edgeSet p` includes `(u, v')` (as a Sym2 element), so `card (edgeSet p) ≥ card (edgeSet p') + 1`.\n\n   We can use that to prove the inequality.\n\n   So:\n   - `card supportSet p ≤ card supportSet p' + 1` (by subset).\n   - By IH: `card supportSet p' ≤ card edgeSet p' + 1`.\n   - So `card supportSet p ≤ (card edgeSet p' + 1) + 1`.\n   - But we have `card edgeSet p ≥ card edgeSet p' + 1`, because `(u, v')` is added to `edgeSet p'` (because `(u, v')` becomes an element of `darts` and `darts p = (u, v') :: darts p'`, so `edgeSet p` is `Sym2.mk (u, v')` + whatever is in `edgeSet p'`, but perhaps it might not be a duplicate edge. However, if `edgeSet p` is the set of edges in `darts p`, then `card edgeSet p ≥ card edgeSet p'` (if not being careful about duplicates, but only that the set is larger).\n   - This seems not to directly give the required inequality. However:\n\n   Actually, perhaps better to use that for `p = cons h p'`, then:\n   - `card supportSet p ≤ card supportSet p' + 1`\n   - `card edgeSet p ≥ card edgeSet p' + 1` unless `(u, v')` is already in `edgeSet p'`.\n   - But perhaps we can't assume that `(u, v')` is not present in `p'`. \n\n   Maybe we need a different invariant. \n\n   I think perhaps `supportSet p.card ≤ edgeSet p.card + 1` is not directly deducible from the `p'` case, because adding `(u, v')` may or may not increment `edgeSet p'`. Hmm.\n\n   An alternative thought is that perhaps for the linked list/double linked list structure of a walk, the number of vertices is at most number of edges + 1. Which is what we have here, except that we're working with sets instead of lists. So `support` is the list of vertices in order, `edgeSet` is the set of edges. And `support.length = edgeSet.length + 1`. If duplicates are removed, then `supportSet.card ≤ support.length = edgeSet.length + 1 ≤ edgeSet.card + edgeSet.length + 1`? But this doesn't directly help.\n\n   Hmm, perhaps another approach is to use the fact that for a walk of length `k`, it has `k+1` vertices (in the list `support`), and `supportSet` is a subset of those `k+1` vertices. So at most `k+1`. And the `edgeSet` is a set of edges with cardinality at least `0` and at most `k`. So `k + 1 ≤ 0 + 1` is false when `k > 0`.\n\n   Oh no, I see that in the actual problem, for `p = cons h p'`, we have that:\n   - The `support` is `u :: p'.support`.\n   - The `darts` is `(u, v') :: p'.darts`.\n   - So if we let `length(p') = k`, then `support` has length `k+2`, and `darts` has length `k + 1`. Wait no: the actual relation is that for `p = cons h p'`:\n     - `length(p) = length(p') + 1`.\n     - `support p = u :: p'.support`, so length is `length(p') + 1`.\n     - `darts p = (u, v') :: p'.darts`, length is `length (p'.darts) + 1`.\n\n   But also for `p'`, `support p' = [v₁, ..., v_{n+1}]`, `darts p' = [(v₁, v₂), ..., (v_n, v_{n+1})]`, which has length `n`, and the support has length `n + 1`. So indeed `length (support) = length (darts) + 1`. \n\n   Hence, for `p`:\n   - `length (support p) = length (darts p' ) + 1 = (length (darts p') + 1) = length (darts p)`, but note that the `length` of the support is equal to the `length` of the `darts` + 1. That is, if the support has length `L`, the `darts` has length `L - 1`.\n\n   Therefore, for a *list*, we get that the length of `support` is `darts.length + 1`.\n\n   Since `supportSet` is a subset of the support, `supportSet.card ≤ support.length = darts.length + 1`.\n   Also, since `edgeSet` is obtained by converting `darts` to Sym2 (a projection), `edgeSet.card ≤ darts.length`. \n\n   Therefore, `supportSet.card ≤ darts.length + 1 ≤ edgeSet.card + 1`? No, that would be decreasing (`edgeSet.card ≤ darts.length`, so `edgeSet.card + 1 ≤ darts.length + 1`, but the direction is reversed).\n\n   Hmm, it seems we get:\n   `supportSet.card ≤ support.length = darts.length + 1`. \n   But `edgeSet.card ≤ darts.length`, so `edgeSet.card + 1 ≤ darts.length + 1`.\n\n   But we want `supportSet.card ≤ edgeSet.card + 1`.\n\n   The difference between `supportSet.card` and `edgeSet.card + 1` is `≤ (darts.length + 1) - (edgeSet.card + 1) = darts.length - edgeSet.card`, which is `≥ 0` because the `edgeSet` is a set of edges derived from `darts`, so its cardinality is `≤ darts.length`.\n\nBut this doesn't give the right inequality.\n\nHmm.\n\nBut actually:\n   `darts` is a list, `edgeSet.card` is `≤ darts.length`. So `edgeSet.card + 1 ≤ darts.length + 1`, but `supportSet.card ≤ darts.length + 1`, because `supportSet.card ≤ support.length = darts.length + 1`.\n\n   So this approach does not yield the desired inequality.\n\n   Adding the concrete case, when all edges are the same, say",
