      "\n  have h₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (p.support.toFinset).card := by\n    simp [supportSet]\n  have h₂ : (p.support.toFinset).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    have h₃ : (p.support.toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ ((p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset : Finset V).card + 1 := by\n      have h₄ : p.support.length ≤ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length + 1 := by\n        induction p with\n        | nil => simp [support, edges, List.length]\n        | cons h p ih =>\n          simp_all [support, edges, List.length, List.map, dartEdge, Sym2.mk.injEq]\n          <;>\n            (try decide) <;>\n            (try omega) <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                cases p <;>\n                  simp_all [support, edges, List.length, List.map, dartEdge, Sym2.mk.injEq]\n                  <;>\n                    omega\n              })\n        | loop p ih =>\n          simp_all [support, edges, List.length, List.map, dartEdge, Sym2.mk.injEq]\n          <;>\n            (try decide) <;>\n            (try omega) <;>\n            (try\n              {\n                cases p <;>\n                  simp_all [support, edges, List.length, List.map, dartEdge, Sym2.mk.injEq]\n                  <;>\n                    omega\n              })\n      have h₅ : (p.support.toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ ((p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset : Finset V).card + 1 := by\n        have h₆ : (p.support.toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ p.support.length := by\n          apply (Finset.card_le_card (Finset.toFinset_subset _ _)).trans\n          <;> simp [List.toFinset_eq_image, Finset.card_image_le]\n        have h₇ : (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset.card ≤ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length := by\n          apply Finset.card_le_of_subset\n          intro x hx\n          simp only [Finset.mem_coe, Finset.mem_image, Finset.mem_filter, Finset.mem_Icc] at hx ⊢\n          <;>\n          (try simp_all [List.mem_map]) <;>\n          (try omega) <;>\n          (try\n            {\n              aesop\n            })\n        have h₈ : p.support.length ≤ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length + 1 := h₄\n        have h₉ : (p.support.toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ ((p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset : Finset V).card + 1 := by\n          calc\n            (p.support.toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ p.support.length := h₆\n            _ ≤ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length + 1 := h₈\n            _ ≤ ((p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset : Finset V).card + 1 := by\n              have h₁₀ : ((p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset : Finset V).card ≥ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length := by\n                have h₁₁ : (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset.card ≥ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length := by\n                  have h₁₂ : (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset.card ≥ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length := by\n                    calc\n                      (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset.card ≥ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset.card := by rfl\n                      _ ≥ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length := by\n                        have h₁₃ : (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset.card ≥ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length := by\n                          have h₁₄ : (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset.card ≥ (p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).length := by\n                            simp_all [List.toFinset_eq_image, Finset.card_image_le]\n                            <;>\n                            (try omega)\n                          exact h₁₄\n                        exact h₁₃\n                  exact h₁₂\n                exact h₁₁\n              omega\n        exact h₉\n      exact h₅\n    have h₁₀ : ((p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card := by\n      simp_all [edgeSet, edges]\n      <;>\n      (try decide) <;>\n      (try omega) <;>\n      (try\n        {\n          cases p <;>\n            simp_all [support, edges, List.map, dartEdge, Sym2.mk.injEq]\n            <;>\n              (try decide) <;>\n              (try omega)\n        })\n    have h₁₁ : (p.support.toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n      calc\n        (p.support.toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ ((p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset : Finset V).card + 1 := h₃\n        _ ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n          have h₁₂ : ((p.edges.map (fun e => e : V → V)).toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card := h₁₀\n          omega\n    exact h₁₁\n  calc\n    (supportSet p).card ≤ (p.support.toFinset).card := h₁\n    _ ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := h₂",
      "this approach is not going to work. Let's try to think differently.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can prove that in the walk, if we ignore duplicate vertices or edges, the number of vertices is ≤ number of edges + 1. \n\nBut perhaps it is easier to prove that the number of vertices is ≤ number of *steps* + 1 (since `support.length = length + 1`, as each step adds one vertex), and then realize that `length = darts.length`, and `edgeSet.card ≤ darts.length`, because each edge occurs at least once in darts (as an unordered pair).\n\nBut we have",
      "\n  - If `u ∈ supportSet q`, then `supportSet p = supportSet q`, so `card(supportSet p) = card(supportSet q)`.\n  - If not, then `card(supportSet p) = card(supportSet q) + 1`.\n- `edgeSet p = { (u, v') } ∪ edgeSet q`.\n  - If `(u, v') ∈ edgeSet q`, then `edgeSet p = edgeSet q`, so `card(edgeSet p) = card(edgeSet q)`.\n  - If not, then `card(edgeSet p) = card(edgeSet q) + 1`.\n\nWe have two cases to consider: \n1. `u ∈ supportSet q`:\n   - Then `card(supportSet p) = card(supportSet q) ≤ card(edgeSet q) + 1` (by IH). \n   - And `edgeSet p ⊇ edgeSet q`, so `card(edgeSet q) ≤ card(edgeSet p)` (since we're taking sets).\n   - Therefore, `card(supportSet p) ≤ card(edgeSet q) + 1 ≤ card(edgeSet p) + 1`.\n   - Wait, but we need `card(supportSet p) ≤ card(edgeSet p) + 1`, which follows if `card(edgeSet q) ≤ card=edgeSet p). But that is not always true: because in this case, if edge `(u,v')` was already in `edgeSet q`, then `card(edgeSet p) = card(edgeSet q)` and it is fine since we get `card(supportSet p) ≤ card=edgeSet p) + 1`.\n   - But if edge `(u,v')` was not in `edgeSet q`, then `card(edgeSet p) = card(edgeSet q) + 1`, so the inequality becomes `card ≤ (edgeSet q) + 1 ≤ (edgeSet q + 1) + 1`.\n   - So this works because in the worst case, we can't decrease the edge count.\n\n   But there is a mistake here: \n   Actually, if `u ∈ supportSet q`, then it is not necessary that `(u,v') ∈ edgeSet q`. In particular, if `q` is the empty walk, this does not hold. Hmm.\n\n   More carefully:\n   - If `u ∈ supportSet q`, then `card(supportSet p) = card(supportSet q)` (no increase).\n   - If `(u, v') ∈ edgeSet q`, then `card(edgeSet p) = card(edgeSet q)` (no increase).\n   - We want to prove `card(supportSet q) ≤ card(edgeSet q) + 1 ≤ card(edgeSet p) + 1`.\n     - If `(u,v') ∈ edgeSet q`, then `card(edgeSet p) = card(edgeSet q)`, and the first inequality is by IH.\n     - If `(u,v') ∉ edgeSet q`, then `card=edgeSet p) = card(edgeSet q) + 1`, and the first inequality is `card(supportSet q) ≤ card(edgeSet q) + 1 ≤ (card=edgeSet q) + 1) + 1` (but this does not directly give what we want). \n       Actually, this branch seems to not help directly. Let me try again:\n\n   The right approach is to realize that for `p = cons h q`, \n   `card(supportSet p) ≤ card(supportSet q) + 1` (since we add at most `u`),\n   and `card(edgeSet p) ≥ card=edgeSet q)` (if we add an edge already present, it does not increase; otherwise it increases by 1).\n   So combining, `card(supportSet p) ≤ card(supportSet q) + 1 ≤ card(edgeSet q) + 1 + 1`. \n\n   But we need `card(supportSet p) ≤ card(edgeSet p) + 1`, and `card(edgeSet p) ≥ card=edgeSet q)`:\n   Therefore `card(supportSet p) ≤ card(edgeSet q) + 2 ≤ card(edgeSet p) + 2`, which is not good enough.\n\n   Hmm, perhaps this approach is not working as is. \n\n2. Alternative approach: Maybe for every new vertex we add, we add an edge. \n\nBut perhaps instead of `supportSet` and `edgeSet`, we should work with the actual lists `support` and `darts`.\n\nActually, for the list `support`, we have `support p = u :: support q`, and for `darts`, we have `darts p = (u, v') :: darts q`.\n\nThen, for multisets, we would have `supportSet p ≤ supportSet q ∪ {u}`, etc. \n\nBut another idea: If we can show that for each time we add a vertex (i.e., when `u ∉ supportSet q`), we also add an edge (i.e., `(u,v') ∉ edgeSet q`), then perhaps the inequality follows.\n\nBut when adding `u`, we also add `(u,v')`. If `u` is new, then `(u,v')` is a new edge if and only if `v'` is not `u`. \n\nBut this is not straightforward. \n\nHmm, perhaps it is better to note that:\n\nFor any list of vertices `v₁, v₂, ..., v_{n+1}`, the number of distinct vertices is `≤ n + 1`, and the number of edge distinct edges is `≥` number of distinct consecutive pairs minus loops. \n\nBut the inequality is actually true in all examples we tried, so perhaps it is generally true, and we need a different approach.\n\n#### Alternative Approach:\nFor any walk, we can c