      "\n     - However, if the support set doesn't increase but the edge set does, or if the edge set doesn't increase but the support set does, it is also fine because the difference is adjusted correctly.\n     - So in the `cons` case, we can use the induction hypothesis on `q` to get `q.supportSet.card ≤ q.edgeSet.card + 1`, and then consider cases based on whether `u` is already in `q.supportSet` and whether `(u, v)` is already in `q.edges`.\n   - However, this seems complicated to formalize directly. Instead, perhaps it's easier to use a more abstract fact from graph theory: the number of edges in a graph is at least the number of vertices minus one. But we are dealing with a walk, not a graph. \n   - Another approach: notice that in any case, `supportSet p.card ≤ support p.length`, and `edges p.length = p.length`, but this doesn't seem directly helpful.\n\nBut perhaps the `cons` case is not that bad:\nWe have:\n```\n(support p).card ≤ (q.support).card + 1\n```\nbecause `support p = u :: q.support`, and the deduplicated version cannot have more elements than `(q.support).card + 1` (whether or not `u` was already in `q.support`).\n\nBut `(q.support).card ≤ (q.edges).card + 1` by the induction hypothesis on `q`.\nAnd also `(p.edges).card = (u,v) :: q.edges).card ≥ q.edges.card` (either equal or +1).\n\nThus:\n```\n(support p).card ≤ (q.support).card + 1 ≤ (q.edges).card + 1 + 1 ≤ (p.edges).card + 1\n```\nHowever, this is not quite correct, because `(q.edges).card + 1 + 1` is not necessarily `≤ (p.edges).card + 1` (unless we know that `(p.edges).card ≥ (q.edges).card + 1`).\n\nAlternatively, perhaps it's better to consider:\n```\n(support p).card ≤ (q.support).card + 1 ≤ (q.supportSet).card + 1 ≤ (q.edgesSet).card + 1 + 1 ≤ (p.edgesSet).card + 2,\n```\nbut this is `≤ (p.edgesSet).card + 2`, and we need `≤ (p.edgesSet).card + 1`.\n\nHmm, perhaps not.\n\nLet me think again: in the `cons h q` case:\n```\n(support p).card = (u :: q.support).toFinset.card ≤ (q.support.toFinset.card) + 1\n```\nbecause inserting `u` into the set can add at most one element.\n\nAnd `(q.support.toFinset.card) ≤ (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1` by induction.\n\nMoreover, `(p.edges.toFinset.card) = ((u,v) :: q.edges).toFinset.card ≥ (q.edges.toFinset.card)` (because we insert one more element).\n\nThus:\n```\n(support p).card ≤ (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1 + 1 = (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 2\n```\nBut `(p.edges.toFinset.card) ≥ (q.edges.toFinset.card)`, so we only get `(support p).card ≤ (p.edges.toFinset.card) + 2`.\n\nThis is insufficient, because we need `≤ (p.edges.toFinset.card) + 1`.\n\nThus, perhaps the original statement is actually false?\n\nBut in all examples above it held. Where did the reasoning go wrong?\n\nAh! The problem is that `(u :: q.support).toFinset.card ≤ (q.support.toFinset.card) + 1` is correct, but the next step is not: we need that `(q.support.toFinset.card) ≤ (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1`, but in reality we only have `(q.supportSet.card) ≤ (q.edgesSet.card) + 1`, i.e., `(q.support.toFinset.card) ≤ (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1` by the induction hypothesis. So combining:\n\n`(support p).card ≤ (q.support.toFinset.card) + 1 ≤ (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 2`.\n\nBut `(p.edges.toFinset.card) = ((u,v) :: q.edges).toFinset.card ≥ (q.edges.toFinset.card)` because inserting `(u,v)` can only keep the same size or increase by one. \n\nBut we need `(q.edges.toFinset.card) + 2 ≤ (p.edges.toFinset.card) + 1`, i.e., `(q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1 ≤ (p.edges.toFinset.card)`. But `(p.edges.toFinset.card) = (q.edges.toFinset.card)` if `(u,v)` is already in `q.edges`, and `(p.edges.toFinset.card) = (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1` otherwise. \n\nTherefore, only in the case where `(u,v)` is not in `q.edges` do we have `(q.edges.toFinset.card) + 2 ≤ (p.edges.toFinset.card) + 1`, which is `(q.edges.toFinset.card) + 2 ≤ ((q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1) + 1` ↔ `true`.\n\nBut if `(u,v)` is already in `q.edges`, then `(p.edges.toFinset.card) = (q.edges.toFinset.card)`, so `(q.edges.toFinset.card) + 2 ≤ (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1` ↔ `2 ≤ 1` which is false!\n\nBut in this case, perhaps `(q.support.toFinset.card) + 1` is actually `≤ (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1`? No, because `(q.support.toFinset.card) ≤ (q.edges.toFinset.card) + 1`, so `(q.support.toFinset.card) +",
      "\n  -- We will prove this by induction on the structure of the LoopWalk.\n  have h₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card +1 := by\n    -- Base case: when the loop walk is nil\n    def loop_walk_card (p : G.LoopWalk u v) : ℕ :=\n      match p with\n      | LoopWalk.nil => 0\n      | LoopWalk.cons _ p => p.length.succ\n      | LoopWalk.loop p => p.length.succ\n    -- Use induction on the loop_walk_card\n    have h₂ : ∀ (p : G.LoopWalk u v), (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n      intro p\n      induction p using LoopWalk.induction_on with\n      | nil =>\n        -- Base case: nil\n        simp [supportSet, edgeSet]\n        <;> aesop\n      | cons h p ih =>\n        -- Inductive step: cons\n        simp_all [supportSet, edgeSet, LoopWalk.darts, LoopWalk.edges, Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem,\n          Finset.mem_singleton, Finset.card_singleton, List.mem_map, List.mem_cons, List.mem_singleton]\n        <;>\n        (try decide) <;>\n        (try omega) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            cases' ih with h₃ h₃ <;>\n            simp_all [supportSet, edgeSet, LoopWalk.darts, LoopWalk.edges, Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem,\n              Finset.mem_singleton, Finset.card_singleton, List.mem_map, List.mem_cons, List.mem_singleton]\n            <;>\n            (try omega)\n          }) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            aesop\n          })\n      | loop p ih =>\n        -- Inductive step: loop\n        simp_all [supportSet, edgeSet, LoopWalk.darts, LoopWalk.edges, Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem,\n          Finset.mem_singleton, Finset.card_singleton, List.mem_map, List.mem_cons, List.mem_singleton]\n        <;>\n        (try decide) <;>\n        (try omega) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            cases' ih with h₃ h₃ <;>\n            simp_all [supportSet, edgeSet, LoopWalk.darts, LoopWalk.edges, Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem,\n              Finset.mem_singleton, Finset.card_singleton, List.mem_map, List.mem_cons, List.mem_singleton]\n            <;>\n            (try omega)\n          }) <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            aesop\n          })\n    -- Apply the induction hypothesis\n    exact h₂ p\n  exact h₁",
