      "edge in edgeSet, we can assign some vertices to it. \n\nBut perhaps better yet, to use that the graph of the walk is connected and apply the lemma that for a connected graph with `V` vertices and `E` edges,",
      "\n  For instance, if we have `p = B-C`, and we do `A-B-C` (i.e., `cons (h : G.Adj A B) p`), then:\n  - `supportSet` goes from {B, C} to {A, B, C}.\n  - `edgeSet` goes from `{ {B,C} }` to `{ {A,B}, {B,C} }`.\n  So the increase in `supportSet.card` is 1 and the increase in `edgeSet.card` is 1, and `(A + 1) ≤ (B + 1) + 1` is true if `A ≤ B`.\n- When we take `LoopWalk.loop`, we add a new edge (e.g., `(A,A)` if we loop at `u = A`), and possibly a new vertex (unsure).\n\nBut `loop p`:\n- The new dart is `(u, u)`, so if you had darts ending with `v` (`[..., (v, u)]`), now you have `[... (v,u), (u, u)]`.\n  So the list of edges becomes `[... {u,v}, {u,u}]`.\n  Now, if `{u,u}` wasn’t there already, it’s added, so the `edgeSet` increases by 1.\n  The `supportSet` doesn’t change because no new vertices are added.\n\nThus, if we are to prove it by induction:\n - For `nil`: `{u}` vs `∅`: 1 ≤ 0 + 1? Well, no. The `darts` of `nil` are `[]`, `edges` is `[]`, `edgeSet` is `∅`, so 1 ≤ 0 + 1. \n   But actually in Lean’s definition, for `nil`, `supportSet = {u}`, `edgeSet = ∅`, and `1 ≤ 0 + 1` is true. \n - For `cons`: we add a new dart `(u, v')` and an edge `{u, v'}` (if not already present), and `supportSet` may or may not increase (if `v'` is already in it, it doesn’t).  So `supportSet.card` increases by at most 1, and `edgeSet.card` increases by at least 0 and at most 1.\n   So, we have `A' ≤ A + 1` and `B' = B + 1 or B' = B`.\n   Then `A' ≤ B' + 1`, because:\n   - If `B' = B + 1`: `A' ≤ A + 1 ≤ (B + 1) + 1 = B' + 1` (by IH).\n   - If `B' = B`: `A' ≤ A + 1`, and by IH `A ≤ B + 1`, so `A' ≤ (B + 1) + 1`. Not sure this helps.\n\nBut perhaps we need a tighter property, such as:\n`(supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1` and the length of the walk is ≥ (supportSet p).card - 1.\n\nHmm, perhaps we can try this approach:\n 1. First, for any walk `p` (not necessarily simple), we have `support p.length ≥ (support p).length - 1`. But in Lean, `length p` is exactly the number of steps (number of darts).\n 2. But we need to connect it with `edgeSet`, which is the number of *distinct* edges. Clearly, `(edgeSet p).card ≤ (darts p).length = (edges p).length`, i.e., `(edgeSet p).card ≤ length p`.\n\nSo:",
      "\n  have h₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    -- Use the fact that the number of vertices is at most the number of edges plus one\n    have h₂ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n      -- Prove by induction on the structure of the loop walk\n      have h₃ : ∀ (u v : V) (p : LoopWalk u v), (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n        intro u v p\n        induction p with\n        | nil =>\n          -- Base case: nil walk\n          simp [supportSet, edgeSet, support, edges, darts]\n          <;> norm_num\n          <;> aesop\n        | cons h p ih =>\n          -- Inductive step: cons case\n          have h₄ := ih\n          simp [supportSet, edgeSet, support, edges, darts, Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem,\n            Finset.mem_singleton, dartEdge, List.mem_map] at h₄ ⊢\n          <;>\n          (try norm_num at h₄ ⊢) <;>\n          (try simp_all [Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem, Finset.mem_singleton, dartEdge, List.mem_map]) <;>\n          (try omega) <;>\n          (try {\n            have h₅ : (u, v) ∉ p.darts := by\n              intro h₆\n              simp [h] at h₆\n              <;>\n              (try contradiction) <;>\n              (try aesop)\n            aesop\n          }) <;>\n          (try {\n            aesop\n          })\n        | loop p ih =>\n          -- Inductive step: loop case\n          simp [supportSet, edgeSet, support, edges, darts, Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem,\n            Finset.mem_singleton, dartEdge, List.mem_map] at ih ⊢\n          <;>\n          (try norm_num at ih ⊢) <;>\n          (try simp_all [Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem, Finset.mem_singleton, dartEdge, List.mem_map]) <;>\n          (try omega) <;>\n          (try {\n            have h₅ : (u, u) ∉ p.darts := by\n              intro h₆\n              simp_all [selfDarts]\n              <;>\n              (try contradiction) <;>\n              (try aesop)\n            aesop\n          }) <;>\n          (try {\n            aesop\n          })\n      -- Apply the general statement to the specific walk p\n      exact h₃ u v p\n    exact h₂\n  exact h₁",
      "\n  have h : p.support.length ≤ (p.edges.length) + 1 := by\n    have h₁ : ∀ (l : List V), l.length ≤ (l.map (fun x => x)).length + 1 := by\n      intro l\n      cases l with\n      | nil => simp\n      | cons x xs =>\n        simp [List.map]\n        <;> ring_nf at *\n        <;> omega\n    -- Use the fact that the support length is bounded by the edges length plus one\n    have h₂ : p.support.length ≤ (p.edges.length) + 1 := by\n      have h₃ : p.support.length ≤ (p.edges.length) + 1 := by\n        -- Prove by induction on the structure of the LoopWalk\n        induction p using LoopWalk.induction with\n        | nil =>\n          simp [support, edges, darts, dartEdge]\n        | cons h q ih =>\n          simp_all [support, edges, darts, concat, append, dartEdge, List.length]\n          <;> try omega\n          <;> try simp_all [List.map, List.cons, List.nil, Nat.succ_eq_add_one]\n          <;> try omega\n          <;> try linarith\n          <;> try nlinarith\n        | loop q ih =>\n          simp_all [support, edges, darts, concat, append, dartEdge, List.length]\n          <;> try omega\n          <;> try simp_all [List.map, List.cons, List.nil, Nat.succ_eq_add_one]\n          <;> try omega\n          <;> try linarith\n          <;> try nlinarith\n      exact h₃\n    exact h₂\n  -- Convert the length bound to a cardinality bound\n  have h₁ : (p.support.toFinset).card ≤ p.support.length := by\n    apply Finset.card_le_of_subset\n    apply Finset.subset_univ\n  have h₂ : p.edges.length = (p.edges.toFinset).card := by\n    have h₃ : ∀ (l : List (Sym2 V)), l.Nodup → l.length = (l.toFinset).card := by\n      intro l h₄\n      rw [Finset.card_eq_sum_ones]\n      simp [h₄, List.sum_map]\n      <;>\n      simp_all [Finset.mem_coe, List.mem_toFinset]\n      <;>\n      aesop\n    have h₄ : p.edges.Nodup := by\n      -- Prove that the edges list is nodup\n      induction p using LoopWalk.induction with\n      | nil =>\n        simp [edges, darts]\n      | cons h q ih =>\n        simp_all [edges, darts, concat, append, dartEdge, List.nodup_cons]\n        <;>\n        try simp_all [Sym2.ext_iff, List.mem_cons, List.mem_singleton]\n        <;>\n        try omega\n        <;>\n        try aesop\n        <;>\n        try\n          {\n            aesop\n          }\n      | loop q ih =>\n        simp_all [edges, darts, concat, append, dartEdge, List.nodup_cons]\n        <;>\n        try simp_all [Sym2.ext_iff, List.mem_cons, List.mem_singleton]\n        <;>\n        try omega\n        <;>\n        try aesop\n        <;>\n        try\n          {\n            aesop\n          }\n    have h₅ : p.edges.Nodup := h₄\n    have h₆ : p.edges.length = (p.edges.toFinset).card := h₃ p.edges h₅\n    exact h₆\n  have h₃ : (p.support.toFinset).card ≤ (p.edges.toFinset).card + 1 := by\n    have h₄ : (p.support.toFinset).card ≤ p.support.length := h₁\n    have h₅ : p.support.length ≤ (p.edges.length) + 1 := h\n    have h₆ : p.edges.length = (p.edges.toFinset).card := h₂\n    have h₇ : (p.support.toFinset).card ≤ (p.edges.toFinset).card + 1 := by\n      calc\n        (p.support.toFinset).card ≤ p.support.length := h₁\n        _ ≤ (p.edges.length) + 1 := h\n        _ = ((p.edges.toFinset).card) + 1 := by rw [h₂]\n    exact h₇\n  -- Use the cardinality bound to conclude the proof\n  have h₄ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    simpa [supportSet, edgeSet] using h₃\n  exact h₄",
      "\n  have h₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length := by\n    simp [supportSet, Finset.card_le_of_subset]\n  have h₂ : (support p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    have h₃ : (support p).length = (support p).length := rfl\n    have h₄ : (edges p).length = (edgeSet p).card := by\n      simp [edgeSet, Finset.card_map]\n      <;>\n      simp_all [edges, support, darts, List.map, List.length]\n      <;>\n      rfl\n    have h₅ : (support p).length ≤ (edges p).length + 1 := by\n      induction p with\n      | nil =>\n        simp [support, edges, darts]\n      | cons u v w h p ih =>\n        simp_all [support, edges, darts, List.length, List.map, Nat.succ_le_succ_iff]\n        <;>\n        (try omega)\n        <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            simp_all [G.Adj]\n            <;>\n            omega\n          })\n        <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            simp_all [G.Adj]\n            <;>\n            linarith\n          })\n      | loop u v p ih =>\n        simp_all [support, edges, darts, List.length, List.map, Nat.succ_le_succ_iff]\n        <;>\n        (try omega)\n        <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            simp_all [G.Adj]\n            <;>\n            omega\n          })\n        <;>\n        (try\n          {\n            simp_all [G.Adj]\n            <;>\n            linarith\n          })\n    have h₆ : (edgeSet p).card = (edges p).length := by\n      rw [h₄]\n    have h₇ : (support p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n      linarith\n    exact h₇\n  have h₃ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    linarith\n  exact h₃",
      "\n  have h₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length := by\n    simp [supportSet]\n    <;>\n    exact Finset.card_le_of_subset (Finset.subset_univ _)\n  have h₂ : (support p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    have h₃ : (support p).length ≤ (darts p).length + 1 := by\n      -- The number of vertices is at most the number of edges plus one\n      have h₄ : ∀ (p : G.LoopWalk u v), (support p).length ≤ (darts p).length + 1 := by\n        intro p\n        induction p with\n        | nil => simp [support, darts]\n        | cons u v' _ h p ih =>\n          simp_all [support, darts, List.length]\n          <;>\n          omega\n        | loop p ih =>\n          simp_all [support, darts, List.length]\n          <;>\n          omega\n      exact h₄ p\n    have h₅ : (darts p).length = (edgeSet p).card := by\n      -- The number of edges is equal to the number of darts\n      simp [edgeSet]\n      <;>\n      simp_all [darts]\n      <;>\n      rw [List.length_toFinset_of_nodup]\n      <;>\n      simp_all [List.nodup_cons, List.nodup_nil]\n      <;>\n      aesop\n    linarith\n  have h₃ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    calc\n      (supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length := h₁\n      _ ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := h₂\n  exact h₃",
      "\n  have h : (supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length := by\n    simp [supportSet]\n    <;> apply (List.toFinset_card_le _).trans\n    <;> simp\n  have h' : (support p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    have h'' : (support p).length = p.support.length := rfl\n    have h''' : (edgeSet p).card = (p.edges).toFinset.card := rfl\n    have h'''' : p.support.length ≤ (p.edges).toFinset.card + 1 := by\n      -- Use the fact that the number of vertices is at most the number of edges plus 1.\n      have h1 : p.support.length = p.length + 1 := by\n        -- Prove that the length of the support is the length of the walk plus 1.\n        have h2 : ∀ (q : G.LoopWalk u v), q.support.length = q.length + 1 := by\n          intro q\n          induction q with\n          | nil => simp [support, length]\n          | cons h q ih =>\n            simp_all [support, length, List.length_cons, Nat.succ_eq_add_one]\n            <;> ring_nf at *\n            <;> simp_all [Nat.succ_eq_add_one]\n            <;> linarith\n          | loop q ih =>\n            simp_all [support, length, List.length_cons, Nat.succ_eq_add_one]\n            <;> ring_nf at *\n            <;> simp_all [Nat.succ_eq_add_one]\n            <;> linarith\n        exact h2 p\n      have h3 : (p.edges).toFinset.card ≥ p.length := by\n        -- Prove that the number of edges is at least the length of the walk.\n        have h4 : (p.edges).toFinset.card ≥ p.edges.length := by\n          -- The number of edges in the set is at least the number of edges in the list.\n          have h5 : (p.edges).toFinset.card ≤ p.edges.length := by\n            -- Actually, the number of edges in the set is at most the number of edges in the list.\n            apply (List.toFinset_card_le _).trans\n            <;> simp\n          -- This is a contradiction, so our assumption must be wrong.\n          -- Wait, no, actually the number of edges in the set is at most the number of edges in the list.\n          -- But we need a lower bound, not an upper bound.\n          -- Hmm, perhaps we should rethink this approach.\n          -- Actually, we don't need this. We can use the fact that the number of edges is at least the number of edges in the list minus duplicates.\n          -- But perhaps it's better to use the fact that the number of edges in the set is at least the number of edges in the list divided by the maximum multiplicity of any edge.\n          -- But perhaps the easiest way is to realize that the number of edges in the set is at least the number of edges in the list minus the number of duplicates.\n          -- But perhaps it's better to prove that the number of edges in the set is at least the number of edges in the list minus the number of duplicates.\n          -- But perhaps we don't need this.\n          -- Actually, perhaps we can just use the fact that the number of edges in the set is at least 0.\n          -- No, that doesn't help.\n          -- Hmm.\n          -- Alternatively, perhaps we can prove that the number of edges is at least the length of the walk.\n          -- But perhaps the number of edges is exactly the length of the walk.\n          -- Yes! Because each cons or loop adds exactly one edge.\n          -- Wait, no. The number of edges is the length of the walk, because each cons or loop adds one edge.\n          -- So, perhaps we can prove that (p.edges).toFinset.card = p.length.\n          -- But that's not necessarily true, because edges can be repeated.\n          -- But perhaps it's better to prove that (p.edges).toFinset.card ≥ p.length.\n          -- No, that's not true either. For example, if all edges are the same, then (p.edges).toFinset.card = 1, but p.length can be large.\n          -- Hmm, perhaps we need a different approach.\n          -- Maybe we can prove that p.support.length ≤ (p.edges).toFinset.card + 1 directly, without going through p.length.\n          -- Let me think about small examples:\n          -- 1. nil: support = [u], edges = [], length = 0.\n          --    p.support.length = 1 ≤ 0 + 1 = 1.\n          -- 2. cons h nil: support = [u, v], edges = [(u, v)], length = 1.\n          --    p.support.length = 2 ≤ 1 + 1 = 2.\n          -- 3. cons h (cons h nil): support = [u, v, v], edges = [(u, v), (v, v)], length = 2.\n          --    p.support.length = 3 ≤ 2 + 1 = 3.\n          -- 4. loop (nil): support = [u, u], edges = [(u, u)], length = 1.\n          --    p.support.length = 2 ≤ 1 + 1 = 2.\n          -- 5. loop (cons h nil): support = [u, u, v], edges = [(u, u), (u, v)], length = 2.\n          --    p.support.length = 3 ≤ 2 + 1 = 3.\n          -- Hmm, it seems that p.support.length = p.length + 1 and (p.edges).toFinset.card ≥ p.length in these examples.\n          -- But in example 2, (p.edges).toFinset.card = 1 = p.length.\n          -- In example 3, (p.edges).toFinset.card = 2 = p.length.\n          -- In example 4, (p.edges).toFinset.card = 1 = p.length.\n          -- In example 5, (p.edges).toFinset.card = 2 = p.length.\n          -- Hmm, actually it seems that (p.edges).toFinset.card = p.length in these examples.\n          -- Is that always true? No: if we have a walk like u-v-u, then edges = [(u, v), (v, u)], but (u, v) = (v, u) in Sym2 V.\n          -- So (p.edges).toFinset.card = 1, but p.length = 2.\n          -- So, no, (p.edges).toFinset.card is not always equal to p.length.\n          -- However, we need p.support.length ≤ (p.edges).toFinset.card + 1, and in this case:\n          -- support = [u, v, u], length = 3, (p.edges).toFinset.card = 1, so 3 ≤ 1 + 1? No, 3 ≤ 2 is false.\n          -- Wait, no: p.edges is [(u, v), (v, u)], and in Sym2 V, these are the same, so (p.edges).toFinset.card = 1.\n          -- And p.support.length = 3. So 3 ≤ 1 + 1 is false.\n          -- But the original statement was (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1, and supportSet p = {u, v}, so card = 2, edgeSet p = {(u, v)}, card = 1, so 2 ≤ 1 + 1 is true.\n          -- So, in fact, the original statement is correct, but our approach of going through p.support.length is not sufficient.\n          -- We need to find a better approach.\n          -- Perhaps instead of trying to relate supportSet p and edgeSet p through support p, we can directly prove (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1.\n          -- The supportSet is the set of vertices, and edgeSet is the set of edges.\n          -- The number of vertices is at most the number of edges plus one.\n          -- But in the example u-v-u, number of vertices = 2, number of edges = 1, so 2 ≤ 1 + 1.\n          -- Hmm, perhaps we can use that the number of vertices is at most the number of edges plus one in any graph.\n          -- But no: for a graph with two vertices and no edges, number of vertices is 2, number of edges is 0, 2 ≤ 0 + 1 is false.\n          -- Hmm, perhaps not.\n          -- Alternatively, perhaps we can use the fact that for a connected graph, the number of vertices is at most the number of edges plus one.\n          -- But our walk may not be connected.\n          -- Alternatively, perhaps we can use induction on the walk.\n          -- Base case: nil. supportSet = {u}, edgeSet = ∅. 1 ≤ 0 + 1.\n          -- Inductive step:\n          -- Suppose it's true for p : LoopWalk v w. Consider cons h p : LoopWalk u w.\n          -- Then supportSet (cons h p) = {u} ∪ supportSet p.\n          -- And edgeSet (cons h p) = { (u, v) } ∪ edgeSet p.\n          -- So, (supportSet (cons h p)).card ≤ (supportSet p).card + 1 ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 + 1 = (edgeSet (cons h p)).card + 1.\n          -- Wait, no, because edgeSet (cons h p) = insert (u, v) (edgeSet p), so (edgeSet (cons h p)).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1.\n          -- Hmm, not sure.\n          -- Also for loop p: supportSet (loop p) = supportSet p, edgeSet (loop p) = insert (u, u) (edgeSet p).\n          -- So (supportSet (loop p)).card = (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 ≤ (edgeSet (loop p)).card + 1.\n          -- Hmm, no: (edgeSet p).card + 1 ≤ (edgeSet (loop p)).card + 1 because (edgeSet (loop p)).card ≥ (edgeSet p).card.\n          -- Not sure.\n          -- Alternatively, perhaps we can use that (supportSet p).card ≤ (p.edges.map (fun e => e.1)).toFinset.card + 1.\n          -- Not sure.\n          -- Alternatively, perhaps we can use that (supportSet p).card ≤ (p.darts).toFinset.card + 1.\n          -- For the nil case: 1 ≤ 0 + 1.\n          -- For cons h p: (supportSet p).card ≤ (p.darts).toFinset.card + 1. And supportSet (cons h p) has at most one new element, u. And (cons h p).dartSet = insert (u, v) p.dartSet. So (supportSet (cons h p)).card ≤ (supportSet p).card + 1 ≤ (p.darts).toFinset.card + 1 + 1. But (cons h p).dartSet.card = (p.darts).toFinset.card + 1 (if (u, v) not in p.darts), or ≤ (p.darts).toFinset.card + 1.\n          -- Hmm, not sure.\n          -- Alternatively, perhaps it's better to try to prove the original statement directly by induction.\n          -- The original statement is (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1.\n          -- Base case: nil. supportSet = {u}, edgeSet = ∅. 1 ≤ 0 + 1.\n          -- Inductive step:\n          -- Case cons h p: supportSet (cons h p) = {u} ∪ supportSet p.\n          -- (supportSet (cons h p)).card ≤ 1 + (supportSet p).card ≤ 1 + ((edgeSet p).card + 1) = (edgeSet p).card + 2.\n          -- But (edgeSet (cons h p)) = insert (u, v) (edgeSet p). So (edgeSet (cons h p)).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1.\n          -- So (supportSet (cons h p)).card ≤ (edgeSet (cons h p)).card + 1 if (edgeSet p).card + 2 ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 + 1, which is true.\n          -- Hmm, but in Lean we have to be careful about whether (u, v) is already in edgeSet p.\n          -- Actually, (edgeSet (cons h p)).card is either (edgeSet p).card or (edgeSet p).card + 1.\n          -- So (supportSet (cons h p)).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 2, but we need ≤ (edgeSet (cons h p)).card + 1 = (edgeSet p).card + 1 or (edgeSet p).card + 2.\n          -- If (edgeSet (cons h p)).card = (edgeSet p).card + 1, then (supportSet (cons h p)).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 2 = (edgeSet (cons h p)).card + 1.\n          -- If (edgeSet (cons h p)).card = (edgeSet p).card, then (u, v) is already in edge",
      "\n  have h₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length := by\n    have h₂ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length := by\n      calc\n        (supportSet p).card = (Finset.card ((support p).toFinset)) := rfl\n        _ ≤ (support p).length := by\n          have h₃ : (support p).toFinset.card ≤ (support p).length := by\n            calc\n              (support p).toFinset.card ≤ (support p).length := by\n                simp [List.toFinset_card_le]\n              _ = (support p).length := by rfl\n          exact h₃\n        _ = (support p).length := by rfl\n    exact h₂\n  \n  have h₂ : (support p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    have h₃ : (support p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n      calc\n        (support p).length = (support p).length := rfl\n        _ ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n          have h₄ : (support p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n            -- Use the fact that the number of vertices in a walk is at most the number of edges plus one.\n            have h₅ : ∀ (l : List V), l.length ≤ (l.map (fun x => (x, x))).length + 1 := by\n              intro l\n              induction l with\n              | nil => simp\n              | cons x xs ih =>\n                simp_all [List.map, List.length]\n                <;> omega\n            -- Apply this fact to the support of the walk.\n            have h₆ : (support p).length ≤ ((support p).map (fun x => (x, x))).length + 1 := h₅ (support p)\n            -- Relate the map to the edge set.\n            have h₇ : ((support p).map (fun x => (x, x))).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card := by\n              -- Use the fact that each edge is counted at most once in the edge set.\n              have h₈ : ((support p).map (fun x => (x, x))).toFinset ⊆ (edgeSet p) := by\n                intro x hx\n                simp only [List.mem_map, Finset.mem_coe, Finset.mem_toFinset] at hx ⊢\n                simp_all [edgeSet, edges, darts, List.mem_map]\n                <;>\n                  (try omega) <;>\n                  (try\n                    {\n                      aesop\n                    }) <;>\n                  (try\n                    {\n                      simp_all [SimpleGraph.LoopWalk]\n                      <;>\n                      aesop\n                    })\n                <;>\n                  (try\n                    {\n                      aesop\n                    })\n              have h₉ : ((support p).map (fun x => (x, x))).toFinset.card ≤ (edgeSet p).card := by\n                apply Finset.card_le_of_subset h₈\n              have h₁₀ : ((support p).map (fun x => (x, x))).length ≥ ((support p).map (fun x => (x, x))).toFinset.card := by\n                simp [List.toFinset_card_le]\n              linarith\n            linarith\n          exact h₄\n        _ = (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by rfl\n    exact h₃\n  \n  have h₃ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card + 1 := by\n    linarith\n  \n  exact h₃",
      "\n  have h₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (support p).length := by\n    simp [supportSet]\n    <;>\n    (try decide) <;>\n    (try simp_all [List.toFinset_card_of_nodup]) <;>\n    (try apply (List.toFinset_card_le _)) <;>\n    (try simp_all [List.nodup_cons, List.mem_cons]) <;>\n    (try omega)\n  have h₂ : (support p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card +1 := by\n    have h₃ : (support p).length = p.length +1 := by\n      induction p with\n      | nil => simp [support, length]\n      | cons h p ih =>\n        simp_all [support, length, List.length]\n        <;>\n        (try omega) <;>\n        (try simp_all [List.length]) <;>\n        (try omega)\n      | loop p ih =>\n        simp_all [support, length, List.length]\n        <;>\n        (try omega) <;>\n        (try simp_all [List.length]) <;>\n        (try omega)\n    have h₄ : (edgeSet p).card ≥ p.length := by\n      have h₅ : p.length ≤ (edgeSet p).card := by\n        have h₆ : p.length = (edges p).length := by\n          induction p with\n          | nil => simp [edges, length]\n          | cons h p ih =>\n            simp_all [edges, length, List.length]\n            <;>\n            (try omega) <;>\n            (try simp_all [List.length]) <;>\n            (try omega)\n          | loop p ih =>\n            simp_all [edges, length, List.length]\n            <;>\n            (try omega) <;>\n            (try simp_all [List.length]) <;>\n            (try omega)\n        have h₇ : (edgeSet p).card ≥ (edges p).length := by\n          have h₈ : (edges p).length ≤ (edgeSet p).card := by\n            calc\n              (edges p).length = (edges p).toFinset.card := by\n                simp [List.toFinset_card_of_nodup]\n                <;>\n                (try decide) <;>\n                (try simp_all [List.nodup_map, List.nodup_cons, List.mem_cons]) <;>\n                (try omega)\n              _ ≤ (edgeSet p).card := by\n                simp [edgeSet]\n          linarith\n        linarith\n      linarith\n    calc\n      (support p).length = p.length +1 := by rw [h₃]\n      _ ≤ (edgeSet p).card +1 := by\n        have h₅ : p.length ≤ (edgeSet p).card := by linarith\n        linarith\n  linarith",
      "\n  have h₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (p.support).length := by\n    -- Prove that the cardinality of the support set is at most the length of the support list\n    have h₁₁ : (supportSet p).card ≤ (p.support).length := by\n      have h₁₂ : (p.support.toFinset : Finset V) = (supportSet p) := rfl\n      rw [h₁₂]\n      -- Use the fact that the cardinality of a finset is at most the length of the original list\n      have h₁₃ : (p.support.toFinset : Finset V).card ≤ (p.support).length := by\n        apply (Finset.card_le_of_subset (Finset.subset_iff.mpr fun x hx => by\n          simp_all [List.mem_toFinset]\n          )).trans\n        -- The length of the list is the number of elements in the list\n        <;> simp [List.length]\n      exact h₁₃\n    exact h₁₁\n  \n  have h₂ : (p.support).length ≤ (p.edges).length + 1 := by\n    -- Prove that the length of the support list is at most the length of the edges list plus one\n    have h₂₁ : (p.support).length ≤ (p.edges).length + 1 := by\n      -- Use induction on the structure of the loop walk\n      have h₂₂ : ∀ (w : G.LoopWalk u v), (w.support).length ≤ (w.edges).length + 1 := by\n        intro w\n        -- Induction on the loop walk\n        induction w using LoopWalk.induction_on <;>\n          simp_all [SimpleGraph.LoopWalk.support, SimpleGraph.LoopWalk.edges,\n            SimpleGraph.LoopWalk.nil, SimpleGraph.LoopWalk.cons, SimpleGraph.LoopWalk.loop,\n            List.length, List.map, List.cons, List.nil]\n        <;>\n          (try decide) <;>\n          (try omega) <;>\n          (try simp_all [Finset.card_eq_zero]) <;>\n          (try ring_nf at * <;> omega)\n      -- Apply the induction result to p\n      have h₂₃ : (p.support).length ≤ (p.edges).length + 1 := h₂₂ p\n      exact h₂₃\n    exact h₂₁\n  \n  have h₃ : (edgeSet p).card = (p.edges).length := by\n    -- Prove that the cardinality of the edge set is equal to the length of the edges list\n    have h₃₁ : (edgeSet p).card = (p.edges).length := by\